<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">
The male of the new species can be easily distinguished from congeners of this genus, except 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. ora" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" rank="species" species="ora">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">B. ora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the thumb-like blunt RTA without a terminal spur (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F7481085" captionText="Figure 3. Bassaniana birudis sp. nov., holotype male. A. Palp in prolateral view; B. Ditto in ventral view; C. Ditto in retrolateral view; D. Ditto in dorsal view; E. Clavate seta; F. Serrated seta (E, embolus; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; VTA, ventral tibial apophysis). Scale bars in mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e73109.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/593313" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">3</figureCitation>
B and, C); versus thumb-like RTA with a spine-like terminal spur in 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. baudueri" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" rank="species" species="baudueri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">B. baudueri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Simon, 1877) (
<bibRefCitation author="Breitling, Rainer" journalOrPublisher="Arachnologische Mitteilungen" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" pagination="38 - 49" refId="B7385039" refString="Breitling, Rainer, Bauer, Tobias, Grabolle, Arno, Oger, Pierre, Pantini, Paolo, Van Keer, Johan, Pfliegler, W. P., Jantscher, Elke, Dolansky, J., 2016. East meets West: on the true identity of Cheiracanthium rupestre and Xysticus albomaculatus (Arachnida: Araneae: Eutichuridae, Thomisidae). Arachnologische Mitteilungen 52: 38 - 49" title="East meets West: on the true identity of Cheiracanthium rupestre and Xysticus albomaculatus (Arachnida: Araneae: Eutichuridae, Thomisidae)." volume="52" year="2016">Breitling et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
: 44, figs. 8-9), 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. decorata" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" rank="species" species="decorata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">B. decorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Karsch, 1879) (
<bibRefCitation author="Paik, K. Y." journalOrPublisher="Educational Journal of the Teacher's College Kyungpook National University" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" pagination="119 - 131" refId="B7385453" refString="Paik, K. Y., 1974. Korean spiders of genus Oxyptila (Araneae, Thomisidae). Educational Journal of the Teacher's College Kyungpook National University 16: 119 - 131" title="Korean spiders of genus Oxyptila (Araneae, Thomisidae)." volume="16" year="1974">Paik 1974</bibRefCitation>
: 120, figs. 5-6), 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. floridana" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" rank="species" species="floridana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">B. floridana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Banks, 1896) (
<bibRefCitation author="Bowling, T. A." journalOrPublisher="Journal of Arachnology" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" pagination="183 - 193" refId="B7385021" refString="Bowling, T. A., Sauer, R. J., 1975. A taxonomic revision of the crab spider genus Coriarachne (Araneida, Thomisidae) for North America north of Mexico. Journal of Arachnology 2: 183 - 193" title="A taxonomic revision of the crab spider genus Coriarachne (Araneida, Thomisidae) for North America north of Mexico." volume="2" year="1975">Bowling and Sauer 1975</bibRefCitation>
: 188, f. 4), 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. utahensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" rank="species" species="utahensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">B. utahensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Gertsch, 1932) (
<bibRefCitation author="Dondale, C. D." journalOrPublisher="Research Branch Agriculture Canada Publication" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" pagination="1 - 255" refId="B7385249" refString="Dondale, C. D., Redner, J. H., 1978. The insects and arachnids of Canada, Part 5. The crab spiders of Canada and Alaska, Araneae: Philodromidae and Thomisidae. Research Branch Agriculture Canada Publication 1663: 1 - 255" title="The insects and arachnids of Canada, Part 5. The crab spiders of Canada and Alaska, Araneae: Philodromidae and Thomisidae." volume="1663" year="1978">Dondale and Redner 1978</bibRefCitation>
: 136, figs. 439 and, 441), and 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. versicolor" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" rank="species" species="versicolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">B. versicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dondale, C. D." journalOrPublisher="Research Branch Agriculture Canada Publication" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" pagination="1 - 255" refId="B7385249" refString="Dondale, C. D., Redner, J. H., 1978. The insects and arachnids of Canada, Part 5. The crab spiders of Canada and Alaska, Araneae: Philodromidae and Thomisidae. Research Branch Agriculture Canada Publication 1663: 1 - 255" title="The insects and arachnids of Canada, Part 5. The crab spiders of Canada and Alaska, Araneae: Philodromidae and Thomisidae." volume="1663" year="1978">Dondale and Redner 1978</bibRefCitation>
: 139, figs. 443 and, 445). The male of the new species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. ora" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" rank="species" species="ora">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">B. ora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the shape of the palpal organ, but can be easily distinguished from the latter by the body appearance, the shape of VTA, tegulum, and embolus: males of 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. birudis" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" rank="species" species="birudis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">B. birudis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. have no white patterns on the carapace and abdominal dorsum (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7383544" captionText="Figure 2. Bassaniana birudis sp. nov., holotype male. A. Habitus in dorsal view; B. Ditto in ventral view; C. Ditto in frontal view; D. Ditto in lateral view; E. Eye area from above; F. Ditto from front; G. Femur; I. in prolateral view (arrow indicates two proximal protuberances). Scale bars in mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e73109.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/575851" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">2</figureCitation>
A), a thick thumb-like VTA (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F7481085" captionText="Figure 3. Bassaniana birudis sp. nov., holotype male. A. Palp in prolateral view; B. Ditto in ventral view; C. Ditto in retrolateral view; D. Ditto in dorsal view; E. Clavate seta; F. Serrated seta (E, embolus; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; VTA, ventral tibial apophysis). Scale bars in mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e73109.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/593313" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">3</figureCitation>
C), a slightly constricted tegulum (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F7481085" captionText="Figure 3. Bassaniana birudis sp. nov., holotype male. A. Palp in prolateral view; B. Ditto in ventral view; C. Ditto in retrolateral view; D. Ditto in dorsal view; E. Clavate seta; F. Serrated seta (E, embolus; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; VTA, ventral tibial apophysis). Scale bars in mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e73109.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/593313" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">3</figureCitation>
B), and an embolus close to the tegulum (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F7481085" captionText="Figure 3. Bassaniana birudis sp. nov., holotype male. A. Palp in prolateral view; B. Ditto in ventral view; C. Ditto in retrolateral view; D. Ditto in dorsal view; E. Clavate seta; F. Serrated seta (E, embolus; RTA, retrolateral tibial apophysis; VTA, ventral tibial apophysis). Scale bars in mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e73109.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/593313" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">3</figureCitation>
B), 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">versus</emphasis>
white marginal patterns on the carapace and abdominal dorsum, a slender finger-like VTA, a round tegulum, and an embolus separated from the tegulum in 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. ora" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" rank="species" species="ora">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">B. ora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Seo, B. K." journalOrPublisher="Korean Arachnology" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" pagination="79 - 84" refId="B7385358" refString="Seo, B. K., 1992. Descriptions of two species of the family Thomisidae from Korea. Korean Arachnology 8: 79 - 84" title="Descriptions of two species of the family Thomisidae from Korea." volume="8" year="1992">Seo 1992</bibRefCitation>
: 79, figs. 1-4).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">Etymology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">
The species name is a combination of Latin prefix 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘bi-’">'bi-'</normalizedToken>
(meaning two) and noun 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘rudis’">'rudis'</normalizedToken>
(meaning small stick) referring to two small rod-like proximal protuberances on the prolateral surface of the femur I (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7383544" captionText="Figure 2. Bassaniana birudis sp. nov., holotype male. A. Habitus in dorsal view; B. Ditto in ventral view; C. Ditto in frontal view; D. Ditto in lateral view; E. Eye area from above; F. Ditto from front; G. Femur; I. in prolateral view (arrow indicates two proximal protuberances). Scale bars in mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e73109.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/575851" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">2</figureCitation>
G).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">
South Korea: Gumi-si, Gyeongsangbuk-do (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7384312" captionText="Figure 1. Distribution map and habitat. A. Distribution of three species of Bassaniana in South Korea; B, C. Habitat of Bassaniana birudis sp. nov." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e73109.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/575893" pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">1</figureCitation>
A).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">Notes</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73109" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">Remarks</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73109">The species was collected with a sweep net between shrubs in a mixed forest of hilly terrain near the tributary of the Nakdonggang River. Currently, females have not been collected and are not known, and no ecological information is available for this species other than its habitat.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
